Haemostasis

  1. The quickest response to endothelial damage is formation of the platelet plug. Platelets roll off the exposed collagen and stick to it.

[!INFO] Platelet activation and aggregation

Adhesion, activation and aggregation. (A) Endothelial injury in the blood vessel exposes collagen to platelets and von Willebrand factors (vWF). (B) Resting platelets attach to the exposed collagen with their glycoprotein surface receptors directly and/or via vWF mediated anchorage. (C) The platelet, upon adhesion to collagen, is activated, changes morphology and releases granular contents which activate more platelets. Activated platelets induce conformational change in a surface receptor, namely, glycoprotein receptor (GP)IIb/IIIa, which induces (D) platelet aggregation via vWF and fibrinogen. (E) Aggregated platelets form a plug at the site of the injury, thereby stopping the blood leakage temporarily. ADP: Adenosine diphosphate; TxA 2 : Thromboxane A 2 ; vWF: von Willebrand factor; GP: glycoprotein receptors. (Figure courtesy of biorender.com).

[!INFO] How to visualize what platelet 'aggregation' means
Prostaglandins influence intra platelet calcium via cAMP;
Ca2+ is required for the processes which produce platelet aggregation and adhesion.

  • prostacylin reduces platelet calcium.
  • Thromboxane increases platelet calcium.

Coagulation cascade and assessment

[!INFO] What is Tissue factor?
AKA Factor III, aka Tissue thromboplastin.
Tissue factor (TF) is best known as the primary cellular initiator of blood coagulation. It is a transmembrane protein.
After vessel injury, the TF:FVIIa complex activates the coagulation protease cascade, which leads to fibrin deposition and activation of platelets Source
Aberrant TF expression triggers intravascular thrombosis associated with various diseases, such as atherosclerosis, cancer, and sepsis

Fibrinolytic system and drugs

  • Low dose aspirin irreversibly inhibits COX-1(and also COX-2) -> inhibits Thromboxane A2 production. See [[Coagulation#^818075|prostacyclin]]
  • Clopidogrel (which is a prodrug) and prasugrel irreversibly inhibit the binding of adenosine to P2Y12 receptors
  • Ticagrelor produces non-competitive reversible inhibition.
  • They inhibit adenosine mediated platelet aggregation.
  • Clopidogrel is the prodrug. It's activated by the CYP2C19 enzyme system which can be inhibited by omeprazole!. Don't co administer the drugs.
  • Prasugrel -> rash and angiooedema rarely.
    • Prasugrel is not used after ischemic stroke / TIA due to increased bleeding risk.
  • 📑Abciximab is a monoclonal antibody which does this;** Only one dose can be given** before the body forms effective antibodies to it.
  • 📑Tirofiban and eptifibatide are also IIb/IIIa blockers which are given IV to reduce early events in ACS.
- These medications function by **inhibiting serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake within the presynaptic terminals**, resulting in elevated concentrations of these neurotransmitters within the synaptic cleft
